', 'domain_gate': 'The immutable wording does not explicitly quantify n and k as integers. Under the stated acceptance criterion, this is a formal blocking defect. All subsequent mathematical branches are conditional on the standard discrete interpretation n,k in Z with 1 <= k <= floor(n/2).', 'validated_core': ['For a >= 2 there is always the representation (a,1), and each fixed lower index k contributes at most one row.', 'Every fiber is finite because a representation implies 2^k <= a.', 'The exact examples M(2)=1, M(6)=2, M(120)=3, and M(3003)=4 are directly certifiable.', 'An exact t=5 witness is equivalent to exactly four interior representations with distinct increasing lower indices and strictly decreasing row indices.'], 'ranked_branches': [{'rank': 1, 'name': 'Two-case negative resolution at t=5', 'assessment': 'Best mathematical fit and decisiveness. Split a hypothetical four-interior fiber according to whether it contains one or at least two indices k>=5. The branch reduces disproof to two explicit compatibility theorems and would settle the original statement as soon as t=5 is excluded.'}, {'rank': 2, 'name': 'Corrected displacement-word algebra', 'assessment': 'Highest immediate information gain. Prescribing three displacement vectors converts a four-point collision into explicit polynomial equations. Small words are finitely falsifiable, and a successful word would produce a concrete t=5 candidate. The reported slope invariant must first be corrected and proved.'}, {'rank': 3, 'name': 'Pell-collision lifting construction', 'assessment': 'Concrete and substantively different from displacement-word search. It starts from an infinite adjacent-column collision family and seeks two independent lifts, such as a triangular representation and another unrelated column. Its main weaknesses are rarity of lifts, exclusion of accidental representations, and lack of a route to arbitrary t.'}, {'rank': 4, 'name': 'Certified exact computation', 'assessment': 'Strong falsification and discovery tool but not a global proof. The strongest scout claim excludes multiplicity at least five through 10^30, yet the reports do not provide a complete independently auditable certificate. Reproduction should guide which algebraic configurations deserve proof effort.'}, {'rank': 5, 'name': 'Uniform arithmetic or geometric bound', 'assessment': 'Potentially decisive but presently least falsifiable. Reduced-denominator divisors, factorial smoothness, carry profiles, prime shadows, and level-chain curvature remain a collection of necessary conditions rather than an absolute multiplicity bound.'}, {'rank': 6, 'name': 'General positive construction for every t', 'assessment': 'Logically indispensable for a positive answer but currently unsupported. Constructing t=5 alone would not prove the original universal statement; a scalable mechanism and uniform exactness control would still be required.'}], 'contradictory_evidence': ['The slope statements in Scouts 2 and 4 are internally inconsistent with their own 3003 example. For the chain (78,2),(15,5),(14,6), row-gap divided by column-gap is 21 then 1, whereas the reciprocal is 1/21 then 1. Any slope-based argument must be rederived before use.', 'Finite-search bounds range from 10^12 to 10^30 and use different enumeration summaries. These are compatible as claims but remain untrusted until one implementation and certificate are independently checked.', 'The Pell construction proves infinitely many pair collisions, but no scout establishes that infinitely many resulting values have an exact fixed multiplicity or admit additional independent lifts.'], 'decision_rule': 'For a negative answer, it is enough to prove that no integer has exactly four interior representations, preferably through the two-case t=5 split. For a positive answer, one must construct exact multiplicity t for every t, not merely produce one t=5 example or prove unbounded multiplicity.'}
